FBIS4-29206 "dreas116_a_94023" FBIS-EAS-94-116 Daily Report 14 Jun 1994 NORTHEAST ASIA Japan Expected Tax Proposals Highlighted Expected Tax Proposals Highlighted OW1406133994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1322 GMT 14 Jun 94 OW1406133994 Tokyo KYODO English BFN [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- Following are highlights of proposals that members of the tax commission Tuesday indicated will be included in a report due out next week. -- Implementing multiyear income and other tax cuts, totaling 6.2 trillion yen a year. -- Hiking the consumption tax, without specific figures but hinting at a raise to at least 7 percent from the current 3 percent. -- The consumption tax hike will be implemented on April 1, 1997, following tax cuts in the previous three years. -- Reviewing the current income and consumption tax system, especially to revamp the ratio of direct and indirect taxes for more fairness. -- Securing net revenue surplus from the tax cut and hike and to spare funds for the aged society in the 21st century. -- Redeeming in 10 to 20 years the 13 trillion yen deficit-covering bonds to be issued to finance 5.5 trillion yen income tax cuts in the current year. -- Avoiding further issuance of deficit-covering bonds. -- Government leadership in fiscal and administrative reforms to win public support for the tax reform asking heavier burdens on taxpayers. -- Drafting tax reform bills by the end of June and enacting them into law by the year-end as promised globally in the March market-opening package. -- Opposing a regional consumption tax, and discussing further the issue of tax revenue sources by the local governments.
